"Peterson A.T., Sánchez-Cordero V., Soberón J., Bartley J., Buddemeier R.W., Navarro-Sigüenza A.G.","Effects of global climate change on geographic distributions of Mexican Cracidae",2001,"Ecological Modelling","144","1",,"21","30",,,10.1016/S0304-3800(01)00345-3,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0035475305&partnerID=40&md5=d058b5abe1104c0562a96e6ae047faf4","Natural History Museum, Biodiversity Research Center, University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States","Peterson, A.T., Natural History Museum, Biodiversity Research Center, University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Sánchez-Cordero, V., Natural History Museum, Biodiversity Research Center, University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Soberón, J., Natural History Museum, Biodiversity Research Center, University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Bartley, J., Natural History Museum, Biodiversity Research Center, University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Buddemeier, R.W., Natural History Museum, Biodiversity Research Center, University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Navarro-Sigüenza, A.G., Natural History Museum, Biodiversity Research Center, University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States","Although climate change and its implications are a frequent subject of detailed study, the effects of these changes on species' geographic distributions remain little explored. We present a first cross-species analysis of the effects of global climate change on the distributions of one bird family, the Cracidae, in Mexico, based on projecting models of ecological niches from present conditions to modeled future conditions taken from general circulation models of climate change. Based on two different scenarios of climate change and on three assumptions regarding species' dispersal abilities, effects on species' distributions range from drastic reduction to modest increases. These results illustrate the complex nature of species' geographic responses to environmental change, and emphasize the need for detailed analysis of individual species' ecological requirements. © 2001 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved.","Biodiversity; Ecological niches; Global climate change; Modeling","bird; climate change; dispersal; geographical distribution; global change; Mexico",,,,,,"Allen, C.D., Breshears, D.D., Drought-induced shift of a forest-woodland ecotone: Rapid landscape response to climate variation (1998) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA, 95, pp. 14839-14842; Austin, M.P., Nicholls, A.O., Margules, C.R., Measurement of the realized qualitative niche: Environmental niches of five Eucalyptus species (1990) Ecol. Monogr., 60, pp. 161-177; Case, T.J., Taper, M.L., Interspecific competition, gene flow, environmental gradients, and the coevolution of species borders (2000) Am. Nat., 155, pp. 583-605; Chapin III, F.S., Zavaleta, E.S., Eviner, V.T., Naylor, R.L., Vitousek, P.M., Reynolds, H.L., Hooper, D.U., Díaz, S., Consequences of changing biodiversity (2000) Nature, 405, pp. 234-242; Crowley, T.J., Causes of climate change over the past 1000 years (2000) Science, 289, pp. 270-277; Davis, A., Jenkinson, L., Lawton, J.H., Shorrocks, B., Wood, S., Making mistakes when predicting shifts in species range in response to global warming (1998) Nature, 391, pp. 783-786; Fielding, A.H., Bell, J.F., A review of methods for the assessment of prediction errors in conservation presence/absence models (1997) Environ. Conserv., 24, pp. 38-49; Guisan, A., Zimmerman, N.E., Predictive habitat models in ecology (2000) Ecol. Mod., 135, pp. 147-186; Higgins, S.I., Richardson, D.M., Cowling, R.M., Trinder-Smith, T.H., Predicting the landscape-scale distribution of alien plants and their threat to plant diversity (1999) Conserv. Biol., 13, pp. 303-313; Holt, R.D., The microevolutionary consequences of climate change (1990) Trends Ecol. Evol., 5, pp. 311-315; Houghton, J.T., Meira Filho, L.G., Callander, B.A., Harris, N., Katt